One of the causes of the perennial political instability and uncertainty in Africa is the winner-take-all system, in which those who win a general election all but capture the state itself and its resources, and those who lose are not only left feeling bitter but typically are treated as enemies of the state, writes Timothy Kalyegira. The Electoral Commission of Uganda Saturday declared National Resistance Movement candidate Yoweri Museveni winner of the 2021 presidential election.
In runner-up position was musician Robert Kyagulanyi, aka Bobi Wine, candidate of the National Unity Platform.
Once again, the election result brings into focus the fate of the candidate who finished second. Under the present system, that runner-up is usually left in a no-man’s-land: he has no position in the next government and next Parliament, and yet commands a huge national following. 



